\begin_layout Section
Code repository
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Historically, DEN projects have been indivually managed.
 This has had the effect that much of the source code and documentation
 produced under DEN umbrella is scattered in various locations, and some
 of it lost.
 This is regrettable because it would be desirable for the lab to have a
 list of past, present, and future projects in addition to their source
 code.
 This could serve as an internal record and also as a public resume of DEN
 work.
 In addition, as a lab which operates highly specialized equipment, having
 sample code is always a plus.
 Recently, I have been using and investigating a piece of project management
 and code repository software named 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Allura"
target "http://sf.net/p/allura"

\end_inset

.
 Allura is the underlying software which powers 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Sourceforge"
target "http://sourceforge.net/"

\end_inset

, and is also known as Sourceforge 2.0.
 It has been released under the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Apache License"
target "http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0"

\end_inset

 and so is free and open-source software.
 I believe that Allura would be a perfect fit to manage new DEN projects
 and archive old projects.
 It would also force all DEN projects to use version control, which I believe
 is a very good thing.
 I have already discussed with Dr.
 Wolffe and Mr.
 Ira Woodring the possiblity of installing this software on a DEN machine.
 Since the install of this software is non-trivial, I would expect that
 working out the best solution for running it would take some time.
 However, due to its advantages, it is definitely worth the effort.
\end_layout

